{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509148"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:13:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11387"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11387","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11387"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.63,0.1,0.04,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4032"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4032","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4032"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11387"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"97"},{"type":"tags","id":"1126"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31047"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner with a two week history of bright red rectal bleeding, severe pain on defaecation and consequent fear of defaecation. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination of the perianal area a small superficial fissure is noted. The patient is advised to increase his dietary fibre intake, to drink plenty of water and use warm sitz baths. He is prescribed topical diltiazem cream and arrangements of made for him to be reviewed in six weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"At which one of the following sites is the fissure most likely to be situated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anterior midline (12 o clock)","Posterior midline (6 o clock)","Left lateral (3 o clock)","Right lateral (9 o clock)","Multiple"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an anal fissure which can be comfortably diagnosed based on history and physical examination. In 90% of cases this occurs in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eposterior midline\u003C/strong\u003E, hypothesised to be due to poor blood supply in this area. In approximately 10% of cases, a fissure occurs in the \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior midline\u003C/strong\u003E however this is usually the case in young women. Both of these sites are considered to be primary fissures and require no further investigation if diagnosed on history and examination. In \u0026lt;1% of patients, a fissure is located either \u003Cstrong\u003Elateral\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Emultiple\u003C/strong\u003E and these are considered secondary fissures. Such fissures raise the concern of an underlying condition such as HIV, Crohns, sarcoidosis or TB, and requires further investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn anal fissure causes spasm of the sphincter, which results in high resting anal pressures, reduced blood supply and local ischaemia which impairs healing. Therefore management involves breaking the cycle of sphincter spasm to allow increased blood supply and facilitate healing. Both warm sitz baths and topical diltiazem (calcium channel blocker) relax the internal anal sphincter and help to break this cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["90% of anal fissures occur in the posterior midline."],"references":["Schlichtemeier S, Engel A. Anal fisures. Australian Prescriber 2016;39(1):14-7. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4816871/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11387"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T09:48:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T09:48:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4032"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"R